# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: akaroa-marine-reserve
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] The area of the park has seen human interaction for approximately 700 years, with evidence of habitation dating back to early Māori iwi such as Waitaha and Rapuwai during the early periods of Māori habitation in New Zealand.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] Following the arrival of Pākehā in the 19th century, the area saw widespread deforestation, farming, and quarrying, significantly modifying the area's environment.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] As a result of this, the park is one of the most modified landscapes of any of New Zealand's national parks, with management of the park largely focusing on regeneration and restoration of the traditional ecosystem.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] The park was first established in 1942 to commemorate the 300th anniversary of Abel Tasman's 1642 visit in New Zealand, when he became the first European to sight the islands.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] It has since been progressively expanded from its original borders, the most recent of which involved the addition of 7 hectares (17 acres) in Awaroa Inlet after a successful crowdfunding campaign.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] The coastal area was inhabited for hundreds of years by Māori prior to the arrival of Europeans, with sites throughout the area occupied both seasonally and permanently.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] In addition to harvesting food from the local forests, estuaries and waters, locals grew kūmara.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] Historical records indicate a pā was established at Auckland Point by Pohea, who travelled there around 1450 from the Whanganui area.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] From the mid-1500s Muaūpoko (formerly known as Ngāi Tara) occupied the area until the early 1600s, when they were ousted by Ngāti Tūmatakōkiri.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] Ngāti Tūmatakōkiri were present when Abel Tasman reached Golden Bay / Mohua in 1642.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] The park was founded in 1942, largely through the efforts of ornithologist and author Pérrine Moncrieff to have land reserved for the purpose.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] Moncrieff served on the park board from 1943 to 1974.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] The park was opened on 18 December 1942 to mark the 300th anniversary of Abel Tasman's visit.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] Those in attendance at the opening ceremony at Tarakohe included Charles van der Plas, as personal representative of the Netherlands' Queen, Wilhelmina.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] The idea for the park had been under consideration since June 1938.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] The Crown set aside 15,225 hectares (37,622 acres), comprising 8,900 hectares (21,900 acres) of proposed state forest, 5,809 hectares (14,354 acres) of Crown land and 554 hectares (1,368 acres) of other reserve land for the national park.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] The Golden Bay Cement Company donated the land where the Abel Tasman Monument and a memorial plaque was sited.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] The area's primary historic interest was the visit of Tasman in 1642, D'Urville in 1827, and the New Zealand Company barques *Whitby* and *Will Watch*, and brig *Arrow* in 1841.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] The site was also of significant botanical interest.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] By 1946 the park had reached 15,534 hectares (38,386 acres) in area with additional land purchases.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] A further 844 hectares (2,085 acres) at Tōtaranui, formerly owned by William Gibbs, was acquired from J S Campbell in 1949 and added to the park.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] About 6,100 hectares (15,000 acres) have been added since.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] In 2008 an extra 7.9 km2 (790 ha; 3.1 sq mi), including the formerly private land known as Hadfields Clearing, were added to the park.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] In 2016, a further 7 hectares (17 acres) in Awaroa Inlet was purchased by New Zealanders in a crowdfunding campaign.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] Covering an area of 237 km2 (92 sq mi; 59,000 acres), the park is the smallest of New Zealand's national parks.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] It consists of forested, hilly country to the north of the valleys of the Tākaka and Riwaka Rivers, and is bounded to the north by the waters of Golden Bay / Mohua and Tasman Bay.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] The park contains some of the islands off the coast including the Tata Islands in Golden Bay / Mohua, and Tonga Island, Motuareronui / Adele Island, and Fisherman Island in Tasman Bay.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] The park does not extend beyond Mean High Water Mark on the adjacent coast.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] Between Mean High Water and Mean Low Water Springs, the beaches are gazetted as a Scenic Reserve, covering 7.74 km2 (2.99 sq mi) in total.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] The Tonga Island Marine Reserve adjoins part of the park.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] The Abel Tasman Monument, though not located in the park, commemorates the first contact between Europeans and Māori and is located near the northern end of the park.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] Abel Tasman National Park stands out from most other National parks of New Zealand, given that a large area of it has undergone extensive environmental modification in its history.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] Early European settlers burned or cleared much of the forest, only to find that the soil was unsuitable for farming.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] This practise not only destroyed much of the shrubland and forests, but also introduced invasive plants found throughout the modern-day park.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] However, as time progresses, the original ecosystems and forests are slowly returning.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] The park contains varied habitats, including coastal forests, sub-alpine bogs, and sand dunes.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] As a result of this diversity, many different species can be found.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] The islands of the park, in particular Tonga Island, Motuareronui / Adele Island and Fisherman Island which are the largest, have been disturbed less and have no introduced mammalian predators.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] As a result the islands have species not found elsewhere in the park and there are more restrictions to visitor access.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] Though much of the parkland is pasture or covered with shrubs, valley areas contain forests of rātā, mataī, miro and hinau.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] Over 70 species of birds have been recorded in the park.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] Some of the birds that can frequently be seen are petrels, shags, penguins, gulls, terns, and herons.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] Possums, wild pigs, deer, and goats can also be seen in the park.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] The Abel Tasman Coast Track is a popular tramping track that follows the coastline and is one of the Department of Conservation's Great Walks; the Abel Tasman Inland Track is less frequented.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] Other walks in the park, such as the Wainui Falls Track are considered "short walks".
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] Kayaking, camping and sightseeing are other activities.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] Access to the park is usually via the small settlement of Mārahau or Kaiteriteri (by water taxi).
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] The nearest large town is Motueka, 20 kilometres (12 mi) to the south.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] Dogs (excepting guide dogs) are not allowed in the park.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] The Department of Conservation administers the National Park.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] The Scenic Reserve is administered by the Tasman District Council Chief Executive and Department of Conservation's Nelson / Marlborough Conservator.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] Activities in adjoining coastal waters are Tasman District Council's responsibility.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] These areas operate under separate regulations.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] The Interior, consisting of the park areas further inland.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] Park plans include ecological surveys, pest control, and protection of heritage areas and caves.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] The Islands, encompassing all islands within the park, some of which are closed to the public. key priorities include keeping them free of invasive pests, reintroducing native species, and minimizing human impacts.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] In 2012 Project Janszoon, a privately funded trust, was set up to restore the park's ecosystems.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] The trust takes its name from Tasman's middle name *Janszoon*.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] It is aiming to complete the restoration in time for the 400th anniversary of Tasman's visit and the park's 100th anniversary in 2042.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] The Department of Conservation and Project Janszoon developed a free virtual visitor centre for downloading to smartphones or tablets.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] The application provides information about the Park's history, its flora and fauna, points of interest, weather, walking tracks, and tides.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/abel-tasman-national-park] This virtual visitor centre is free of charge and can be found through the App Store or Google Play Store.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Aboriginal title is also referred to as **indigenous title**, **native title** (in Australia), **original Indian title** (in the United States), and **customary title** (in New Zealand).
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Aboriginal title jurisprudence is related to indigenous rights, influencing and influenced by non-land issues, such as whether the government owes a fiduciary duty to indigenous peoples.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] While the judge-made doctrine arises from customary international law, it has been codified nationally by legislation, treaties, and constitutions.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Aboriginal title was first acknowledged in the early 19th century, in decisions in which indigenous peoples were not a party.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Significant aboriginal title litigation resulting in victories for indigenous peoples did not arise until recent decades.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] The majority of court cases have been litigated in Australia, Canada, Malaysia, New Zealand, and the United States.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Aboriginal title is an important area of comparative law, with many cases being cited as persuasive authority across jurisdictions.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Legislated Indigenous land rights often follow from the recognition of native title.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Aboriginal title arose at the intersection of three common law doctrines articulated by the Judicial Committee of the Privy Council: the Act of State doctrine, the Doctrine of Continuity, and the Recognition Doctrine.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] The Act of State doctrine held that the Crown could confiscate or extinguish real or personal property rights in the process of conquering, without scrutiny from any British court, but could not perpetrate an Act of State against its own subjects.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] The Doctrine of Continuity presumed that the Crown did not intend to extinguish private property upon acquiring sovereignty, and thus that pre-existing interests were enforceable under British law.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Its mirror was the Recognition Doctrine, which held that private property rights were presumed to be extinguished in the absence of explicit recognition.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] In 1608, the same year in which the Doctrine of Continuity emerged, Edward Coke delivered a famous dictum in *Calvin's Case* (1608) that the laws of all non-Christians would be abrogated upon their conquest.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Coke's view was not put into practice, but was rejected by Lord Mansfield in 1774.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] The two doctrines were reconciled, with the Doctrine of Continuity prevailing in nearly all situations (except, for example, public property of the predecessor state) in *Oyekan v Adele* (1957).
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] The first Indigenous land rights case under the common law, *Mohegan Indians v.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Connecticut*, was litigated from 1705 to 1773, with the Privy Council affirming without opinion the judgement of a non-judicial tribunal.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] The requirements for establishing an aboriginal title to the land vary across countries, but generally speaking, the aboriginal claimant must establish (exclusive) occupation (or possession) from a long time ago, generally before the assertion of sovereignty, and continuity to the present day.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Aboriginal title does not constitute allodial title or radical title in any jurisdiction.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Instead, its content is generally described as a usufruct, i.e. a right to use, although in practice this may mean anything from a right to use land for specific, enumerated purposes, or a general right to use which approximates fee simple.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Especially in Australia, the content of aboriginal title varies with the degree to which claimants are able to satisfy the standard of proof for recognition.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] In particular, the content of aboriginal title may be tied to the traditions and customs of the indigenous peoples, and only accommodate growth and change to a limited extent.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Aboriginal title can be extinguished by the general government, but again, the requirement to do this varies by country.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Some require the legislature to be explicit when it does this, others hold that extinguishment can be inferred from the government's treatment of the land.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] In Canada, the Crown cannot extinguish aboriginal title without the explicit prior informed consent of the proper aboriginal title holders.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] New Zealand formerly required consent, but today requires only a justification, akin to a public purpose requirement.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Jurisdictions differ on whether the state is required to pay compensation upon extinguishing aboriginal title.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Theories for the payment of compensation include the right to property, as protected by constitutional or common law, and the breach of a fiduciary duty.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Australia did not experience native title litigation until the 1970s, when Indigenous Australians (both Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people) became more politically active, after being included in the Australian citizenry as a result of the 1967 referendum.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] In 1971, Blackburn J of the Supreme Court of the Northern Territory rejected the concept in *Milirrpum v Nabalco Pty Ltd* (the "Gove land rights case").
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] The Aboriginal Land Rights Commission was established in 1973 in the wake of *Milirrpum*.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Paul Coe, in *Coe v Commonwealth* (1979), attempted (unsuccessfully) to bring a class action on behalf of all Aborigines claiming all of Australia.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] The Aboriginal Land Rights Act 1976, established a statutory procedure that returned approximately 40% of the Northern Territory to Aboriginal ownership; the Anangu Pitjantjatjara Yankunytjatjara Land Rights Act 1981, had a similar effect in South Australia.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] The High Court of Australia, after paving the way in *Mabo No 1* by striking down a State statute under the *Racial Discrimination Act 1975*, overruled *Milirrpum* in *Mabo v Queensland (No 2)* (1992).
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] *Mabo No 2*, rejecting *terra nullius*, held that native title exists (6–1) and is extinguishable by the sovereign (7–0), without compensation (4–3).
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] In the wake of the decision, the Australian Parliament passed the Native Title Act 1993 (NTA), codifying the doctrine and establishing the National Native Title Tribunal (NNTT).
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] *Western Australia v Commonwealth* upheld the NTA and struck down a conflicting Western Australia statute.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] In 1996, the High Court held that pastoral leases, which cover nearly half of Australia, do not extinguish native title in *Wik Peoples v Queensland*.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] In response, Parliament passed the Native Title Amendment Act 1998 (the "Ten Point Plan"), extinguishing a variety of Aboriginal land rights and giving state governments the ability to follow suit.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] This decision did not involve indigenous peoples, but was an important example of the key doctrines that underlie aboriginal title.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] In 1996, the Toledo Maya Cultural Council (TMCC) and the Toledo Alcaldes Association (TAA) filed a claim against the government of Belize in the Belize Supreme Court, but the Court failed to act on the claim.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] In 2007, Chief Justice Abdulai Conteh ruled in favor of the Maya communities of Conejo and Santa Cruz, citing the IACHR judgement and key precedents from other common law jurisdictions.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] The government entered into negotiations with the Maya communities, but ultimately refused to enforce the judgement.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] A Botswana High Court recognized aboriginal title in *Sesana and Others v Attorney General* (2006), a case brought by named plaintiff Roy Sesana, which held that the San have the right to reside in the Central Kalahari Game Reserve (CKGR), which was violated by their 2001 eviction.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] The decision quoted *Mabo* and other international case law, and based the right on the San's occupation of their traditional lands from time immemorial.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] The court described the right as a "right to use and occupy the lands" rather than a right of ownership.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] The government has interpreted the ruling very narrowly and has allowed only a small number of San to re-enter the CKGR.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Aboriginal title has been recognized in Common Law in Canada since the Privy Council, in *St.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] The Queen* (1888), characterized it as a personal usufruct at the pleasure of the Queen.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] This case did not involve indigenous parties, but rather was a lumber dispute between the provincial government of Ontario and the federal government of Canada.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Catharines* was decided in the wake of the Indian Act (1876), which laid out an assimilationist policy towards the Aboriginal peoples in Canada (First Nations, Inuit, and Métis).
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] It allowed provinces to abrogate treaties (until 1951), and, from 1927, made it a federal crime to prosecute First Nation claims in court, raise money, or organize to pursue such claims.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Section 91(24) of the Constitution Act, 1867 ("British North America Act 1867") gives the federal government exclusive jurisdiction over First Nations, and thus the exclusive ability to extinguish Aboriginal title.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Section Thirty-five of the Constitution Act, 1982 explicitly recognized and preserved aboriginal rights.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Guerin* (1982), the first Supreme Court of Canada decision handed down after the Constitution Act 1982, declared that Aboriginal title was *sui generis* and that the federal government has a fiduciary duty to preserve it.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Syliboy* (1929) which had held that Aboriginal peoples had no capacity to enter into treaties, and thus that the Numbered Treaties were void.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] A variety of non-land rights cases, anchored on the Constitution Act 1982, have also been influential.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Subsequent decisions have drawn on the fiduciary duty to limit the ways in which the Crown can extinguish Aboriginal title, and to require prior consultation where the government has knowledge of a credible, but yet unproven, claim to Aboriginal title.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] In 2014 the Supreme Court ruled unanimously for the plaintiff in *Tsilhqot'in Nation v.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] It also stated that governments must have consent from First Nations which hold Aboriginal title in order to approve developments on that land, and governments can override the First Nation's wishes only in exceptional circumstances.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] The court reaffirmed, however, that areas under Aboriginal title are not outside the jurisdiction of the provinces, and provincial law still applies.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] In 2008, Japan gave partial recognition to the Ainu people.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] However, land rights were not given for another eleven years.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] In 2019, Japan fully recognised the Ainu people as the indigenous people of Japan and gave them some land rights if requested.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Malaysia recognised various statutory rights related to native customary laws (*adat*) before its courts acknowledged the independent existence of common law aboriginal title.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Native Customary Rights (NCR) and Native Customary Land (NCL) are provided for under section 4(2) of the National Land Code 1965, the Sarawak Land Code 1957, the respective provisions of the National Land Code (Penang and Malacca Titles) Act 1963, and the Customary Tenure Enactment (FMS).
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Rajah's Order IX of 1875 recognized aboriginal title by providing for its extinguishment where cleared land was abandoned.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Rajah's Order VIII of 1920 ("Land Order 1920") divided "State Lands" into four categories, one of them being "native holdings", and provided for the registration of customary holdings.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] The Aboriginal People's Act 1954 creates aboriginal areas and reserves, also providing for state acquisition of land without compensation.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Article 160 of the Federal Constitution declares that custom has the force of law.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Malaysian court decisions from the 1950s on have held that customary lands were inalienable.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] In the 1970s, aboriginal rights were declared to be property rights, as protected by the Federal Constitution.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Decisions in the 1970s and 1980s blocked state-sanctioned logging on customary land.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] In 1997, Mokhtar Sidin JCA of the Jahore High Court became the first Malaysian judge to acknowledge common law aboriginal title in *Adong bin Kuwau v.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] The High Court cited the Federal Constitution and the Aboriginal Peoples Act, as well as decisions from the Privy Council, Australia, Canada, New Zealand, and the United States.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] That case was the first time where Orang Asli directly and expressly challenged a state taking of their land.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] The opinion held that: "the aborigines' common law rights include, inter alia, the right to live on their land as their forefathers had lived." The case was upheld on appeal, but the Federal Court did not write an opinion.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Later High Court and Court of Appeal decisions built upon the foundation of *Adong bin Kuwau*.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] However, the ability for indigenous peoples to bring such suits was seriously limited by a 2005 ruling that claims must be brought under O.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] 53 RHC, rather than the representative action provision.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] In 2007, the Federal Court of Malaysia wrote an opinion endorsing common law aboriginal title for the first time in *Superintendent of Lands v.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] New Zealand was the second jurisdiction in the world to recognize aboriginal title, but a slew of extinguishing legislation (beginning with the New Zealand land confiscations) has left the Māori with little to claim except for river beds, lake beds, and the foreshore and seabed.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] In 1847, in a decision that was not appealed to the Privy Council, the Supreme Court of the colony of New Zealand recognized aboriginal title in *R v Symonds*.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] The decision was based on common law and the Treaty of Waitangi (1840).
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Chapman J went farther than any judge—before or since—in declaring that aboriginal title "cannot be extinguished (at least in times of peace) otherwise than by the free consent of the Native occupiers".
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] That court created the "1840 rule", which converted Māori interests into fee simple if they were sufficiently in existence in 1840, or else disregarded them.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] *Symonds* remained the guiding principle, until *Wi Parata v the Bishop of Wellington* (1877).
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] *Wi Parata* undid *Symonds*, advocating the doctrine of *terra nullius* and declaring the Treaty of Waitangi unenforceable.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] The Privy Council disagreed in *Nireaha Tamaki v Baker*, and other rulings, but courts in New Zealand continued to hand down decisions materially similar to *Wi Parata*.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] The Coal Mines Amendment Act 1903 and the Native Land Act 1909 declared aboriginal title unenforceable against the Crown.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Eventually, the Privy Council acquiesced to the view that the Treaty was non-justiciable.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Land was also lost under other legislation.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] The Counties Act 1886 s.245 said that tracks, "over any Crown lands or Native lands, and generally used without obstruction as roads, shall, for the purposes of this section, be deemed to be public roads, not exceeding sixty-six feet in width, and under the control of the Council".
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Opposition to such confiscation was met by force, as at Opuatia in 1894.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] A series of Acts, beginning a year after the Treaty of Waitangi with the Land Claims Ordinance 1841, allowed the government to take and sell 'Waste Lands'.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Favorable court decisions turned aboriginal title litigation towards the lake beds, but the Māori were unsuccessful in claiming the rivers the beaches, and customary fishing rights on the foreshore.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] The Limitation Act 1950 established a 12-year statute of limitations for aboriginal title claims (6 years for damages), and the Maori Affairs Act 1953 prevented the enforcement of customary tenure against the Crown.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] The Treaty of Waitangi Act 1975 created the Waitangi Tribunal to issue non-binding decisions, concerning alleged breaches of the Treaty, and facilitate settlements.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Circa the Te Ture Whenua Māori Act 1993, less than 5% of New Zealand was held as Māori customary land.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] The Court also indicated that customary aboriginal title interests (non-territorial) might also remain around the coastline.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] The Foreshore and Seabed Act 2004 extinguished those rights before any lower court could hear a claim to either territorial customary title (the Maori Land Court) or non-territorial customary rights (the High Court's inherent common law jurisdiction).
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] That legislation has been condemned by the Committee on the Elimination of Racial Discrimination.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] The 2004 Act was repealed with the passage of the Marine and Coastal Area (Takutai Moana) Act 2011.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] The Supreme Court of Papua New Guinea followed suit.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Schedule 2 of the Constitution of Papua New Guinea recognizes customary land tenure, and 97% of the land in the country remains unalienated.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] In *Alexkor v Richtersveld Community* (2003), a suit under the Restitution of Land Rights Act 1994, lawyers gathered case law from settler jurisdictions around the world, and judges of the Constitutional Court of South Africa talked frankly about Aboriginal title.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] The Land Claims Court had dismissed the complaint of the Richtersveld peoples, whose land was seized by a government owned diamond mining operation.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] The Supreme Court of Appeal disagreed, citing *Mabo* and *Yorta Yorta*, but held that the aboriginal title had been extinguished.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Whether the precedent will be the start of further land rights claims by indigenous peoples is an open question, given the cut-off date of 1913 in the Restitution Act.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] The case ultimately did not lead to the inclusion of the Aboriginal title in South African doctrine.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Legal scholars allege that this is because the application of terms like 'indigenous' and 'Aboriginal' in a South African context would lead to a number of contradictions.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] The identity of the indigenous groups in South Africa is not self-evident.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] The adoption of a strict definition, including only communities descended from San and Khoekhoe people, would entail the exclusion of black African communities, an approach deemed detrimental to the spirit of national unity.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] The legacy of the Natives Land Act also means that few communities retain relationships with the land of which they held before 1913.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Taiwanese indigenous peoples are Austronesian peoples, making up a little over 2% of Taiwan's population; the rest of the population is composed of ethnic Chinese who colonised the island from the 17th century onward.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] From 1895 Taiwan was under Japanese rule and indigenous rights to land were extinguished.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] In 1945, the Republic of China (ROC) took control of Taiwan from the Empire of Japan; a rump Republic of China was established on Taiwan in 1949 after the Communists won the Chinese Civil War.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] From then, indigenous people's access to traditional lands was limited, as the ROC built cities, railroads, national parks, mines and tourist attractions.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] In 2005 the Basic Law for Indigenous Peoples was passed.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] In 1976, the Barabaig people challenged their eviction from the Hanang District of the Manyara Region, due to the government's decision to grow wheat in the region, funded by the Canadian Food Aid Programme.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] The wheat program would later become the National Agricultural and Food Corporation (NAFCO).
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] NAFCO would lose a different suit to the Mulbadaw Village Council in 1981, which upheld customary land rights.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] The Court of Appeal of Tanzania overturned the judgement in 1985, without reversing the doctrine of aboriginal title, holding that the specific claimants had not proved that they were native.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] The Extinction of Customary Land Right Order 1987, which purported to extinguish Barabaig customary rights, was declared null and void that year.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] In 1999, the Maasai were awarded monetary compensation and alternative land by the Court of Appeal due to their eviction from the Mkomazi Game Reserve when a foreign investor started a rhino farm.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] The government has yet to comply with the ruling.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] The United States, under the tenure of Chief Justice John Marshall, became the first jurisdiction in the world to judicially acknowledge (in *dicta*) the existence of aboriginal title in series of key decisions.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Marshall envisioned a usufruct, whose content was limited only by "their own discretion", inalienable except to the federal government, and extinguishable only by the federal government.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Early state court decisions also presumed the existence of some form of aboriginal title.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Later cases established that aboriginal title could be terminated only by the "clear and plain intention" of the federal government, a test that has been adopted by most other jurisdictions.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] The federal government was found to owe a fiduciary duty to the holders of aboriginal title, but such duty did not become enforceable until the late-20th century.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] These bodies have no authority to title land, only to pay compensation.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Alcea Band of Tillamooks* (1946) was the first ever judicial compensation for a taking of Indian lands unrecognized by a specific treaty obligation.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] United States* (1955) established that the extinguishment of aboriginal title was not a "taking" within the meaning of the Fifth Amendment.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Unlike Australia, Canada, and New Zealand, the United States allows aboriginal title to be created post-sovereignty; rather than existing since pre-sovereignty, aboriginal title need only have existed for a "long time" (as little as 30 years) to be compensable.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Unlike most jurisdictions, the doctrine that aboriginal title is inalienable never took hold in India.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Sales of land from indigenous persons to both British subjects and aliens were widely upheld.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] The Pratt–Yorke opinion (1757), a joint opinion of England's Attorney-General and Solicitor-General, declared that land purchases by the British East India Company from the Princely states were valid even without a Crown patent authorizing the purchase.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] In a 1924 appeal from India, the Privy Council issued an opinion that largely corresponded to the Continuity Doctrine: *Vaje Singji Jorava Ssingji v Secretary of State for India*.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] This line of reasoning was adopted by the Supreme Court of India in a line of decisions, originating with the proprietary claims of the former rulers of the Princely states, as well as their heirs and assigns.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Adivasi land rights litigation has yielded little result.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aboriginal-title] Most Adivasi live in state-owned forests.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] As an inner city suburb, Addington has a mix of residential, retail and light industrial properties.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] Addington is sited between the suburbs of Spreydon and Riccarton, with Blenheim Road providing the boundary to Riccarton.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] The cluster of the shops in the suburb of Spreydon also provide a clear boundary between the suburbs.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] To the east of the suburb is Sydenham and to the west is Middleton.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] For the first decade after the founding of Christchurch in 1850, Addington was farmland, consisting of large rural sections.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] In the early 1860s the railway was surveyed through the area and subdivision of the larger sections began.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] Factories moved in; wool and grain sheds opened; and with the industry came residential development for workers.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] Development continued throughout the 19th century.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] The city's sale yards opened in 1874 and the railway workshops were moved to Addington in 1880.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] By the time the show grounds were opened in 1887, Addington had become an important suburb in the industrial and social life of Christchurch.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] In 1874 the Addington Prison was built under the guidance of Benjamin Mountfort in Lincoln Road.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] The prison closed in 1999 and the Mountfort cell block and remaining perimeter walls are a Heritage New Zealand Historic Place Category 2 and is now a hostel.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] The suburb was named for the country residence of Archbishop John Sumner, one of the leading members of the Canterbury Association, and who was buried in St Mary's Church, Addington in England.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] The New Zealand Railways Department's Addington Workshops were situated in Addington until their closure in the 1990s.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] The historic concrete water-tower is the only remnant of the workshops.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] The tower has served as the centrepoint for the Tower Junction shopping complex.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] A new Christchurch railway station at Addington opened in 1994 to replace the former station on Moorhouse Avenue.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] The station mainly serves the TranzAlpine which carries passengers on the 223-kilometre (139 mi) coast-to-coast journey from Christchurch to Greymouth.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] Addington was the home of the oldest blending plant in the Southern Hemisphere until it was demolished after sustaining some damage in the February 2011 Christchurch earthquake.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] The demolition of the plant sparked some controversy as the plant had been lined up to be carefully taken apart in an attempt to save Oregon timber valued at over $600,000.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] Addington comprises four statistical areas.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] Addington North is primarily industrial, with the Main South Line running through it.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] Addington West and Addington East are residential.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] Tower Junction has a shopping centre, Addington Racecourse, and light industrial premises, and also includes two rest homes, which result in an unusually high median age for residents.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] The residential areas of Addington, comprising the statistical areas of Addington West and Addington East cover 1.13 km2 (0.44 sq mi).
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] They had an estimated population of 6,040 as of June 2025, with a population density of 5,345 people per km2.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] The statistical areas of Addington West and Addington East had a population of 5,346 at the 2018 New Zealand census, an increase of 315 people (6.3%) since the 2013 census, and an increase of 1,059 people (24.7%) since the 2006 census.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] Ethnicities were 60.4% European/Pākehā, 10.7% Māori, 4.5% Pasifika, 29.8% Asian, and 4.0% other ethnicities.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] People may identify with more than one ethnicity.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] The percentage of people born overseas was 41.0, compared with 27.1% nationally.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] Although some people chose not to answer the census's question about religious affiliation, 40.1% had no religion, 41.7% were Christian, 0.5% had Māori religious beliefs, 4.3% were Hindu, 2.1% were Muslim, 1.1% were Buddhist and 4.2% had other religions.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] Of those at least 15 years old, 1,212 (26.1%) people had a bachelor's or higher degree, and 780 (16.8%) people had no formal qualifications.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] The employment status of those at least 15 was that 2,544 (54.7%) people were employed full-time, 519 (11.2%) were part-time, and 183 (3.9%) were unemployed.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] Addington North covers 0.43 km2 (0.17 sq mi).
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] It had an estimated population of 110 as of June 2025, with a population density of 256 people per km2.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] Statistics New Zealand do not publish detailed statistics for areas of very low population.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] Tower Junction covers 1.07 km2 (0.41 sq mi).
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] It had an estimated population of 180 as of June 2025, with a population density of 168 people per km2.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] Tower Junction had a population of 120 at the 2018 New Zealand census, an increase of 81 people (207.7%) since the 2013 census, and an increase of 96 people (400.0%) since the 2006 census.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] There were 12 households, comprising 42 males and 78 females, giving a sex ratio of 0.54 males per female.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] Ethnicities were 80.0% European/Pākehā, 2.5% Māori, 5.0% Pasifika, and 15.0% Asian.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] The percentage of people born overseas was 30.0, compared with 27.1% nationally.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] Although some people chose not to answer the census's question about religious affiliation, 22.5% had no religion, 70.0% were Christian and 2.5% had other religions.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] Of those at least 15 years old, 12 (10.3%) people had a bachelor's or higher degree, and 45 (38.5%) people had no formal qualifications.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] The median income was $22,500, compared with $31,800 nationally.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] The employment status of those at least 15 was that 24 (20.5%) people were employed full-time, and 6 (5.1%) were part-time.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] Tower Junction shopping centre is located in Addington, owned by Ngāi Tahu.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] It opened in 2002, and was redeveloped in 2018.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] It covers 37,000 m2 and has 40 tenants, including Toyworld, Bunnings and Harvey Norman.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] The suburb is home to multiple sporting and events complexes, including Horncastle Arena, Rugby League Park (currently branded as Orangetheory Stadium), and Addington Raceway.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] Along with Riccarton Racecourse, the Raceway is one of Christchurch's primary horse-racing venues, focusing predominantly on harness racing, and is the home to the annual New Zealand Trotting Cup.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] Addington is also close to many other event venues, notably Hagley Park to the north and the Canterbury Agricultural Park to the southwest.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] Central to Addington's residential area is St Mary's Anglican Church, which is a historic building surrounded by the spacious grounds and trees of Church Square.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] The grounds are used by the community for galas, pancake races (on Shrove Tuesday) fairs and weddings.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] The buildings and surrounding area is registered by Heritage New Zealand as a historic area, with registration number 7516.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] Addington was also formerly home to an immigration barrack.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] The Court Theatre, whose buildings were damaged in the earthquake, relocated to "The Shed" and started operating in 2011.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] Manuka Cottage is a community house that serves the interests of a wide variety of people and local community groups.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] Addington School is sited in the south–west corner of the suburb where the boundary with Spreydon is not clearly defined.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] It is a contributing primary school for years 1 to 6.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] The school opened in 1881 as West Christchurch Side School, the original building was built from timber but burnt down in 1909.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/addington-new-zealand] Sacred Heart School is a Catholic state-integrated full primary school for years 1 to 8.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] An **administrative centre** is a seat of regional administration or local government, or a county seat or town, or the place where the central administration of a commune or equivalent subdivision, is located.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] In countries with French as an administrative language, such as Belgium, Luxembourg, Switzerland and many African countries, a ***chef-lieu*** (French pronunciation: [ʃɛfljø], pl.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] 'chief place' or 'main place') is a town or city that is important from an administrative perspective.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] The capitals of Algerian provinces, districts, and communes are called *chefs-lieux*.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] The *chef-lieu* in Belgium is the administrative centre of each of the ten provinces of Belgium.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] Three of these cities also give their name to their province (Antwerp, Liège and Namur).
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] The *chef-lieu* of a French department is known as the prefecture (*préfecture*).
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] This is the town or city where the prefect of the department (and all services under their control) are situated, in a building also known as the prefecture.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] In every French region, one of the departments has preeminence over the others, and the prefect carries the title of *préfet de la région* (lit.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] 'Prefect of the Region') or *préfet du département* (lit.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] 'Prefect of the Department') and the city where the regional prefect is found is known as the *chef-lieu* of the region.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] The services are, however, controlled by the prefecture of the department.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] The *chef-lieu* of an arrondissement, commonly known as the *sous-préfecture* is the city or town where the sub-prefect of the arrondissement (and the services directly under their control) are situated, in a building called the sub-prefecture.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] The arrondissement where the department prefecture is located does not normally have a sub-prefect or sub-prefecture, the administration being devolved usually to the secretary-general of the departmental prefecture, who functions as sub-prefect for the arrondissement.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] The *chef-lieu* of a canton is usually the biggest city or town within the canton, but has only a nominal role.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] No specific services are controlled by it.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] In past decades, there was always a gendarmerie, a treasurer and a justice of the peace.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] The *chef-lieu* indicates the principal city of the provinces of New Caledonia.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] So Nouméa is the chef-lieu of South Province.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] But the chef-lieu can also mean the principal area within a town.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] So Wé is part of the town of Lifou, but is the chef-lieu of Lifou.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] In the Loyalty Islands and the other islands, the name of the chef-lieu differs from that of the name of the town.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] For the towns of the mainland, the chef-lieu has the same name as the town.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] Nouméa is a town composed only of Nouméa.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] Many of the West African states which gained independence from France in the mid-20th century also inherited the French administrative structure of departments and communes, headed by a *chef-lieu*.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] States still using *chef-lieu* to identify the administrative headquarters of a government subdivision include Senegal, Burkina Faso, Benin, Mali, and Niger.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] Taking Niger and Mali as examples, the administrative subdivisions down to the commune level each have a formal place of administrative headquarters, titled the *chef-lieu*.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] The larger portion of the terminology of administrative division is inherited from colonial rule as part of French West Africa, and has survived and been somewhat modified over time.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] In both nations there have been remarkably parallel histories.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] Since decentralization began in both nations in the 1990s, the *chef-lieu* transitioned from the location of the governor, commandant, or prefect and their staff to the location of the commune, cercle, department, and regional councils and a variety of decentralized bodies.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] The **chef-lieu** of a region, cercle or department is usually also a communal **chef-lieu**.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] Both nations also established a supreme council of local government authorities (*Haut conseil des collectivités territoriales*) seated at the nation's capital.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] Smaller subdivisions in Mali's communes (villages, tribal councils, and quarters) are administered from a *place* (lit.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] 'site'), so the *chef-lieu* is literally the 'chief-place' even at the lowest level.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] In Jordan, the administrative centres are known as chief towns or *nahias*.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] Nahias may be in charge of a sub-district (*qda*), a district (*liwa*), or a governorate (*muhafazah*).
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] Luxembourg is divided into four electoral constituencies, twelve cantons, as well as 100 communes (Luxembourgish: *Gemengen*).
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] Cantons have each a *chef-lieu* and are named after it.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] The same is true for each commune which is composed of more than one town or village.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] Usually, with a few exceptions, the commune is named after the communal *chef-lieu*.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] In Russia, several million-plus cities in federal districts have the official status of an administrative centre: Moscow (as the main city of the Central Federal District), Vladivostok, Volgograd, Yekaterinburg, Nizhny Novgorod, Novosibirsk, Pyatigorsk, Rostov-on-Don and St.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] The main cities of regions and municipal districts are also called unofficially the administrative centre or simply the centre.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] The only exception to this rule is the republics, for which the term "capital" is used to refer to the seat of government.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] The capital of Russia is also an entity to which the term "administrative centre" does not apply.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] In Sweden there are two levels of administrative centre; the local municipal and the regional county.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] Central locality (Swedish: *centralort*) is a term commonly ascribed to the settlement that serves as a municipal administrative centre.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] This level handles the local administrative and political tasks of the surrounding settlements.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] Since central place theory was the guiding principle during the 1962–1977 municipal reform, most municipalities were dominated by a larger urban area where the political seat was located.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] Most municipalities are named for their central locality, but there are several exceptions.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] There are many deviations from the central locality principle.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] Some municipalities are dominated by two or more towns of similar size, and sometimes they share the municipal administration, with the municipality having its official address in one of the towns.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] For example, both Skillingaryd and Vaggeryd are central localities of Vaggeryd Municipality.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] Conversely, there are municipalities within metropolitan areas.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] For example, there are twenty-six municipalities within the Stockholm metropolitan area.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] The term "central locality" has no legal meaning and it is unclear how it should be applied to these municipalities.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] Some municipalities appointing one or several localities to be the central locality.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] A residence city (Swedish: *residensstad*) is the town or city which is the political and administrative seat of the county.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] This level handles the more regional political and administrative tasks of the county, such as healthcare and public transport.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] The name comes from these towns or cities being where the governor (*landshövding*) resides.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] The term *chef-lieu* is applied to the capital of each Swiss canton.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] In 16 of the 26 cantons, the territory is subdivided into districts.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] Every district's capital is also termed a *chef-lieu* and each has a prefect.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] The term *chef-lieu* is used to designate the capital of each governorate of Tunisia.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] Each of the 24 governorates is subdivided into delegations which each have a central city as the *chef-lieu* of the delegation.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] In the United Kingdom, an administrative centre is the centre of a local authority, which is distinct from the county town of a historic county.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/administrative-centre] For example, the administrative centre where the county council of Lancashire sits is Preston, even though the county town is Lancaster.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/ahuriri-conservation-park] The mountains, forests, tussock lands and river valleys are used for tramping, fishing kayaking, horse riding and hunting.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/ahuriri-conservation-park] Both the park and neighbouring Ben Avon Station are located near the Aoraki Mackenzie International Dark Sky Reserve, a dark-sky preserve, and are used for astronomy.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/ahuriri-conservation-park] The town is serviced by the tourist town of Omarama.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/ahuriri-conservation-park] The park was established in 2005, and includes the Birchwood Station leasehold farm the New Zealand Government bought back for NZ$10 million in 2004.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/ahuriri-conservation-park] It contained extensive wetlands that had remained largely undeveloped.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/ahuriri-conservation-park] Birchwood Station continued normal farming operations until the end of the leasehold in 2010.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/ahuriri-conservation-park] The road to the former Birchwood Station homestead stopped being regularly maintained by Waitaki District Council in 2011.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/ahuriri-conservation-park] In 2014, ecologist Peter Espie reported a decrease in native plant species in the park, and suggested introducing grazing management.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/ahuriri-conservation-park] Parts of the 2020 Disney film *Mulan* were filmed in the Ahuriri Valley near the conservation park, including the training camp scenes and some battle scenes.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aidanfield] Aidanfield is located between Halswell Road (State Highway 75), Dunbars Road, the Christchurch Southern Motorway, the Canterbury Agricultural Park (home of the Canterbury A&P Show) and Templetons Road.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aidanfield] The centre of Aidanfield is about 8 kilometres (5.0 mi) from Christchurch city centre.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aidanfield] Father Laurence Ginaty established the Mount Magdala Institute in 1886 to provide a home for women and girls.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aidanfield] It developed into an institution caring for women recently released from prison, orphans, and "unruly girls".
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aidanfield] Numerous buildings were constructed, and at its peak in the 1930s, 500 people lived on the complex.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aidanfield] The St John of God Chapel, designed by Sidney and Alfred Luttrell and now listed as a Category I heritage structure by Heritage New Zealand, was completed in 1912.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aidanfield] The Catholic order owned all the land around Mount Magdala, and decided to develop most of it as a subdivision to provide them with financial support.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aidanfield] *The Press* first reported in mid-2000 on the subdivision plans.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aidanfield] The suburb is named after Mother Aidan Phelan (1858–1958), the Superior at Mount Magdala from 1907 to 1920 and again from 1929 to 1936.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aidanfield] Mother Aidan was herself named after the Irish saint Aidan of Lindisfarne.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aidanfield] The name Aidanfield was approved on 31 January 2001.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aidanfield] It had an estimated population of 4,070 as of June 2025, with a population density of 2,423 people per km2.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aidanfield] Aidanfield had a population of 3,903 at the 2018 New Zealand census, an increase of 1,011 people (35.0%) since the 2013 census, and an increase of 2,607 people (201.2%) since the 2006 census.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aidanfield] There were 1,242 households, comprising 1,842 males and 2,064 females, giving a sex ratio of 0.89 males per female.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aidanfield] Ethnicities were 64.0% European/Pākehā, 3.8% Māori, 1.2% Pasifika, 33.1% Asian, and 2.7% other ethnicities.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aidanfield] The percentage of people born overseas was 35.9, compared with 27.1% nationally.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aidanfield] Although some people chose not to answer the census's question about religious affiliation, 46.6% had no religion, 43.9% were Christian, 0.1% had Māori religious beliefs, 1.5% were Hindu, 0.8% were Muslim, 1.5% were Buddhist and 1.3% had other religions.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aidanfield] Of those at least 15 years old, 960 (30.4%) people had a bachelor's or higher degree, and 465 (14.7%) people had no formal qualifications.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aidanfield] The median income was $33,600, compared with $31,800 nationally.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aidanfield] The employment status of those at least 15 was that 1,488 (47.1%) people were employed full-time, 456 (14.4%) were part-time, and 69 (2.2%) were unemployed.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aidanfield] The first residents moved into Aidanfield in 2002, and by 2011 some 400 sections had been built on; when the subdivision is fully developed, more than 50 new roads will have been created.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aidanfield] The 2006 New Zealand census reported 1320 residents in the Aidanfield area unit.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aidanfield] Statistics New Zealand have estimated the suburb's 2010 population at 2400 residents.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aidanfield] The subdivision developer caused controversy in 2007 after applying to have four of the five historic Magdala Farm buildings demolished to make way for further subdivision.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aidanfield] Although the buildings were protected in the Christchurch City Council District Plan, councillors voted eight to four in favour of granting demolition consent.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aidanfield] There are no shopping facilities in Aidanfield; the nearest shops are in neighbouring Halswell, about 2.5 kilometres (1.6 mi) away.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aidanfield] A multi-sports complex, Ngā Puna Wai Sports Hub, is located in Aidanfield.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aidanfield] The Halswell Residential College is a school for boys with learning difficulties, from years 7 to 10.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aidanfield] Located on Mount Magdala land, the school had a roll of 13 as of March 2026 and is decile 2.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aidanfield] After the 2011 Christchurch earthquake, Discovery 1 School and Unlimited Paenga Tawhiti (UPT) used the campus of this school.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aidanfield] UPT moved to Ilam in 2013, whilst Discovery 1 remained at the Halswell Residential College, until the two schools, now merged as Ao Tawhiti, moved to a new site in the central city.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aidanfield] Aidanfield Christian School is a state-integrated school for years 1 to 10.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/aidanfield] Also on Mount Magdala land, it had a roll of 451 as of March 2026 and is decile 7.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-harbour] The name Akaroa is an alternative spelling of Whakaroa, Whangaroa or Wangaloa from the Kāi Tahu dialect of Māori.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-harbour] The harbour was used commercially in the mid-19th century for ship-based and shore-based whaling.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-harbour] Cruise ships occasionally enter the harbour, with the passengers visiting Akaroa.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-harbour] Ōnawe Peninsula is at the head of the harbour, the former site of a Māori pā.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-harbour] Akaroa Harbour's waterfront has been continually inhabited since the 1840s.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-harbour] Ōnuku, Akaroa, Takapūneke, Takamatua, Robinsons Bay, Duvauchelle, Barrys Bay, French Farm, Tikao Bay and Wainui lie on the shoreline of the harbour.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-harbour] They are connected to the rest of Canterbury via State Highway 75.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-harbour] French Bay, the site of the French settlement of Akaroa, was originally known as Paka Ariki.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-harbour] The Akaroa Harbour statistical area covers the settlements around the harbour with the exception of Akaroa.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-harbour] It had an estimated population of 780 as of June 2025, with a population density of 4.8 people per km2.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-harbour] Akaroa Harbour had a population of 729 at the 2018 New Zealand census, a decrease of 27 people (−3.6%) since the 2013 census, and an increase of 18 people (2.5%) since the 2006 census.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-harbour] There were 330 households, comprising 363 males and 366 females, giving a sex ratio of 0.99 males per female.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-harbour] Ethnicities were 93.8% European/Pākehā, 6.6% Māori, 1.2% Pasifika, 2.5% Asian, and 2.5% other ethnicities.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-harbour] The percentage of people born overseas was 21.0, compared with 27.1% nationally.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-harbour] Although some people chose not to answer the census's question about religious affiliation, 49.4% had no religion, 39.9% were Christian, 1.2% had Māori religious beliefs, 0.8% were Buddhist and 1.2% had other religions.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-harbour] Of those at least 15 years old, 159 (24.4%) people had a bachelor's or higher degree, and 90 (13.8%) people had no formal qualifications.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-harbour] The median income was $28,100, compared with $31,800 nationally.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-harbour] The employment status of those at least 15 was that 279 (42.9%) people were employed full-time, 132 (20.3%) were part-time, and 3 (0.5%) were unemployed.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-harbour] The harbour is one of two eroded volcanic centres from the extinct Banks Peninsula Volcano.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-harbour] The 475-hectare (1,170-acre) Akaroa Marine Reserve was given approval in 2013 after a 17-year campaign to get it established.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-harbour] As of 2011, of the seven sites that are sampled in the harbour for water quality, six are graded as "good" and one as "fair" in terms of recreational use.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-harbour] In late January 2026 a wildlife cruise, the *Black Cat*, became grounded at Nīkau Palm Valley Bay.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-harbour] There were 38 passengers and three crew on board the catamaran.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-harbour] The vessel was carrying more than 2000 litres of marine diesel fuel, which spilled into the harbour.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-harbour] Less than two months later, a Royal New Zealand Navy vessel spilled 200-300 litres of oil into the harbour during a training exercise.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] Akaroa Marine Reserve and the nearby Pōhatu Marine Reserve are no-take zones.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] The harbour as a whole has considerable natural values, and the fauna of the inner and outer harbour differs.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] There are pressures on the ecology from human activity, such as settlements on the edge of the harbour, and land and water-based industrial activity.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] The marine boundary of Akaroa Marine Reserve is almost entirely surrounded by Akaroa Taiāpure, which occupies the rest of the harbour and the ocean coast between the Akaroa and Pōhatu reserves.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] The taiāpure is a local fishing co-management tool for the harbour, which has customarily been of special significance to the hapū as a source of food for spiritual and cultural reasons.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] The taiāpure was established over 90 percent of the harbour in February 2006.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] It allows Te Rūnanga o Ngāi Tahu (tribal council) and other fisheries stakeholders to have a say in how the harbour is managed.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] Fishing can continue in taiāpure, subject to rules and regulations.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] The taiāpure complements the reserve (the remaining 10% of the harbour), as does Pōhatu Marine Reserve just outside the harbour entrance, in Pōhatu / Flea Bay, plus Lyttelton Harbour's Port Levy Mātaitai Reserve and Rāpaki Mātaitai Reserve.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] A *mātaitai* is a permanent reserve created in areas of traditional importance to Māori for customary food gathering.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] The two marine reserves are total no-take areas, whereas the taiāpure and mātaitai are fishing enabling and not about the protection of marine life.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] Indeed, the *tangata tiaki* (marine guardian) has the power to override fishing regulations, and moreover, the taking of kelp by one pāua farmer is enshrined in the taiāpure legislation.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] The Akaroa Taiāpure Management Committee is a non-elected group largely made up of Ngāi Tahu representatives and a range of fisheries interest groups, including recreational, commercial, marine farmers and marine tourism operators.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] This committee has no control over the number of recreational anglers, hence no control over the total number of fish and shellfish taken.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] Throughout the 1980s and 1990s, people with local knowledge knew that fish stocks were nowhere near as plentiful as they once were.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] Māori who had fished the harbour for decades had lost the opportunity of fishing freely along its shoreline.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] The *rūnanga* (committee of senior decision-makers of an *iwi* (tribal group) or *hapū* (family, district groups or community)) knew that pollution and over-fishing had diminished the area of available *mahinga kai* (traditional food gathering areas) within the harbour.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] Pollution includes sewage, farm and sub-division run-off as well as algal blooms.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] Forest and Bird carried out exploratory dives in Akaroa Harbour in 1990.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] The Akaroa Harbour Marine Protection Society formally proposed the establishment of a 560-hectare (1,400-acre) marine reserve in 1996.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] The proposal was divisive and led to a two-decade battle that pitted a small group of vocal and determined local residents and divers against recreational anglers, *rūnanga*, commercial fishers and one aquaculturalist.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] The local residents wanted a no-take area in the eastern waters of the outer harbour to acts as a breeding pool and as place for dolphins to feed.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] Recreational anglers argued "that's where we fish in a northeasterly".
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] Te Runanga o Ngāi Tahu claimed strong ties to the area, naming it Te Whata o Kōkiro (meaning the food store-house of Kokiro).
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] When the marine reserve idea was first mooted, commercial fishing was a part of Akaroa's economy and commercial fishers strongly opposed it.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] During the long battle, fish stock declined, and so did commercial fishing.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] The original proposal called for a reserve within the harbour.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] Fishers counteracted that proposal by applying for and getting a smaller 215 hectares (530 acres) hectares reserve to be located outside of the harbour, at sheltered bay named Pōhatu / Flea Bay.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] While eco-tourism operators were pleased to have something to show to tourists, local iwi continued to express concerns that marine reserves hindered their traditional rights to harvest from the sea.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] Meanwhile, the local residents group continued to advocate for a reserve within the harbour.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] The Fisheries Act 1996 Part 9 Section 174–175 provides for the establishment of taiāpure/fisheries co-management by local people who care about and have strong ties to an area.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] In January 2004, the Māori Land Court tribunal made a recommendation to the Minister of Fisheries that a taiāpure be granted over the whole of Akaroa Harbour bar one small area subject to the, at that time, proposed Akaroa Marine Reserve.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] Judge Wainwright saw no reason why the two could not live together.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] However, this recommendation was successfully appealed by the local pāua farmer and kelp harvester, who claimed a taiāpure would compromise his business.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] The High Court sent the case back to the tribunal to gather further evidence about whether the whole of Akaroa Harbour does or does not come within the concept of "littoral coastal waters" of "special cultural significance" to the rūnanga.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] The pāua farmer eventually reached an understanding with Ngāi Tahu, ending years of argument.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] He has been granted the rights to harvest giant bladder kelp (*Macrocystis pyrifera*), which he uses to feed the pāua at the Akaroa Paua Farm and also to make garden fertiliser and kelp pepper.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] In contrast, the East Otago Taiāpure explicitly prohibits the harvesting of kelp.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] That ban does not extend to unattached beach-cast kelp.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] There are environmental concerns in Akaroa Harbour regarding the ecological disruption caused by kelp harvesting to wild pāua and other *kaimoana* (sea food).
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] The taiāpure was established in February 2006, but the marine reserve took eight more years.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] Conservation Minister Kate Wilkinson declined the application for the reserve in 2010 on the grounds that it would adversely affect recreational fishing.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] The decision was challenged in the High Court and was quashed in a 2012 ruling.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] In terms of actual numbers, the two separate consultation processes for the application had attracted more support than opposition.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] In April 2013 Conservation Minister Nick Smith announced the approval of the reserve but at the reduced size of 465 hectares (1,150 acres).
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] Smith believed the battle had gone on for too long.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] The size was reduced to take into account the concerns about customary and recreational fishing.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] Subsequently, the size was finalised as 512 hectares (1,270 acres).
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] Environment Minister Amy Adams expressed an aspiration for the next step to be integrating the local management of taiāpure and reserve so the two mechanisms work together.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] New Zealand fishing rules place reduced bag limits on many fish species and prohibit shellfish gathering in specific areas.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] Tangata tiaki (marine guardians) are appointed for Ōnuku Runanga *rōhe moana* (defined customary fishing area) by the Minister of Primary Industries.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] The tangata tiaki (also known as kaitiaki) receive training in bylaws, what quantities of various species can be taken, dates or seasons recommended for harvest, size limits and methods of harvest.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] Fishers can get a kaitiaki permit from the tangata tiaki granting permission to take over and above the catch limit, and under the legal size.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] This permit, colloquially called a "chit", is given for *tangihanga* (funeral), *hui* (gathering) and other occasions.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] In addition to upping catch limits, the kaitiaki has the power to override other fishing regulations.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] In 2018, the Department of Conservation trialled a baited underwater video study, which provided a snapshot of the fish communities both within and outside the Akaroa and Pōhatu marine reserves.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] A total of 28 fish species were identified, demonstrating that the baited underwater video technique is an effective method for examining the size and relative abundance of these species.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] The study found notable differences in the relative abundances and sizes of blue cod and blue moki in the marine reserves when compared to three taiāpure control areas.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] However, since there is no baseline data for Akaroa Marine Reserve, it would be hasty to link these spatial variations to their protection status.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] Nonetheless, the results indicated an increase in the abundance and size of blue cod and moki at Pōhatu reserve compared to earlier studies, and that is likely due to the protection from direct fishing pressure.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] In 2021, a three-year initiative called *Iongairo* was launched to supply data that aids in the management of customary fishing zones and enhances understanding of marine reserves in Te Pātaka o Rākaihautū/Banks Peninsula.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] *Iongairo* focused on identifying and evaluating important habitats—including rock, sand, and mud—and key species such as pāua, mussels, and various types of seaweed.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] Additionally, it examined the effects of human activities on the environment.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] Methods included baited underwater cameras, towed and dropped cameras, along with sediment grabs.
[src:akaroa-marine-reserve/akaroa-marine-reserve] The outcome is an interactive online map showcasing the seafloor.
